Dear Hiring Team,

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the *Open Source Developer* role with *Figma*. I bring over three years of professional experience building scalable front-end systems, extensible developer tooling, and production AI pipelines, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my engineering roles, I have built and shipped production-grade systems that directly reflect the open-source, collaborative, and TypeScript-driven technical depth this position demands. As a Software Engineer at Sperse, I designed a React and TypeScript node-based visual workflow platform enabling users to compose, run, and manage real-time collaborative agentic pipelines through a highly interactive user interface — backed by Temporal for durable execution and Redis for live progress streaming across concurrent sessions. Alongside it, I created a production MCP server using FastMCP that exposed 160+ API actions as an extensible SDK layer over a multi-tenant backend, enabling external developers to integrate and automate content management workflows across enterprise customers — an experience that mirrors Figma's focus on empowering developers to extend and integrate with the platform. To keep these systems production-ready, I built GitHub Actions CI/CD pipelines with OpenTelemetry trace-based evals scoring latency, accuracy, and safety — gating every release with open-source-style reproducible build and distribution workflows. I also engineered RAG agents with LlamaIndex, OpenAI embeddings, and Pgvector using Prompt Engineering techniques to auto-generate ready-to-run REST API examples for developer onboarding. Prior to Sperse, at Qualitest, I designed a cloud-agnostic Storage Service in Java and Spring Boot satisfying enterprise scalability, security, governance, and design system requirements, and reduced query latency by optimizing PostgreSQL with window functions and materialized views — surfacing results through interactive React TypeScript visualizations for complex data model requirements that stakeholders relied on daily. Together, these roles have prepared me to architect scalable front-end systems, lead 0→1 open-source initiatives, and contribute meaningfully to Figma's ecosystem of developer-facing tools.

My independent project work has given me direct experience leading 0→1 open source products from design through community launch. I led development of Dark Factory — a distributed coding-agent orchestrator that decomposes large requests into dependency-aware task DAGs executed across multi-machine AI agents — shipping it as an open source project with documentation targeting community adoption. I architected TypeScript-based SDK boundaries and plugin-style agent integrations so external contributors can extend orchestration behavior, applying the same extensible software design patterns valued in developer tooling and API frameworks. This hands-on experience building for an external developer community, maintaining documentation, and designing for extensibility is precisely what Figma's open-source mission requires — and has shaped me into an engineer who builds with community growth in mind.

I have always been passionate about making powerful tools accessible to all and fostering multiplayer collaboration that unlocks creativity at scale — and envision myself contributing my talent to the furthering of Figma's mission to make design accessible to all. I would love to discuss my interest in this position with your team and can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration, I look forward to connecting!

